p://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Dont be so fast to judge the result.</span><hr size=1> I would not be surprised if we learn to harness vacuum energy in the sometime future. The potential is unlimited.<br>
<br>
There is a downside, tho.<br>
<br>
Arthur C. Clarke has suggested that some hypernovas and gamma-ray bursters are simply industrial accidents by civilizations using vacuum energy.<br>
<br>
I was thinking last night about Fermi's Paradox: Why haven't we detected aliens yet?<br>
<br>
In the famous Drake Equation, one of the factors is longevity of the civilization. If a society survives only briefly, then they most likely won't be detected.<br>
<br>
The limit has been the likelihood of nuclear war or ecological destruction.<br>
<br>
I wonder if messing with things like strangelets and vacuum energy may not be the major factor.<br>
<br>
Possibly every society eventually learns the technology and instantly and accidentally erases itself from the universe.<br>
<br>
Rather morbid.<br>
<br>
If it IS controllable, space-faring would be a breeze.<br>
